		<body>
			<pb n="1R"/>
				<p rend="align(right)"><placeName>St Louis</placeName> <date>November 6<hi rend="sup">th</hi> 1849</date></p>
				<p><addressee>Revd. Isaac Leeser</addressee></p>
			<p rend="indent(2)">Dear Sir</p>
			<p rend="indent(3)">Knowing the interest you take<lb/> in the welfare of your coreligionists&#44; throughout the<lb/> Union&#44; I therefore avail myself of the opportunity<lb/> afforded me of communicating with you.</p>
				<p>The congregation to which I belong and to which<lb/> I have the honor of being Secretary has increased so<lb/> rapidly within the last twelve months &#40;so much<lb/> beyond our most sanguine expectations&#41; that I<lb/> am sure you will participate with us in our<lb/> exultations.  At our last Holy Days our<lb/> synagogue was crowded to almost suffocation<lb/> not less than from Five to Six hundred persons<lb/> being present.  When but a few years ago<lb/> we could but boast of fifty or sixty and it is<lb/> still increasing.  We have been more than<lb/> fortunate in securing the valuable services of<lb/> the <persName>Revd. Nathan Davidson</persName>&#44; a gentleman qualified<lb/> in an eminent degree for the offices he now<lb/> fills&#44; which is rather more than ordinary&#44;<lb/> arduous&#44; being Shocet as well as Hasan&#44;<lb/> having myself been a constant attender both<lb/> to the <placeName>London</placeName> and <placeName>New York</placeName> synagogues I<lb/> consider myself justified in saying that he<lb/> cannot be surpassed in his style of Reading</p>
				<p rend="The following is written in pencil at the top right corner of the page.">W &#58; Agent&#58; <persName role="author">Henry Meyers</persName> <date>1849</date>&#63;</p>
			<pb n="1V"/>
				<p>his <sic>pronounciatin</sic> being most perfect and his<lb/> singing clear from those additions so often made<lb/> use of.  You may think my Dear Sir that I have<lb/> over drawn my picture&#44; but I am sure had you<lb/> been present&#44; and seen the satisfaction depicted<lb/> upon the countenances of his hearer as thy life<add>&#63;</add><lb/> the House of Prayer&#44; after hearing the Revd gentleman<lb/> you would agree with me&#44; that I have fell<lb/> far short in my c<add>&#63;</add>.  There is also a<lb/> new German Synagogue started which in a<lb/> little time will become of importance&#44; we have<lb/> also two Benefit docu<add>&#63;</add> both flourishing&#44;<lb/> and we are about organising a <sic>Benevelent</sic><lb/> Society for the Relief of our less fortunate<lb/> Bretheren&#44; the progress of which I will inform<lb/> you of at some future day in the mean<lb/> time Dear Sir Believe me</p>
			<p rend="indent(5)">to be your most obdt. Servant</p>
			<p rend="indent(6)"><persName role="author">Henry Meyers</persName> Secretary</p>
			<p rend="indent(6)"><hi rend="underline">United Hebrew Congregation</hi></p>
			<p rend="indent(7)"><persName><sic>Myers</sic></persName></p>
			<pb n="2V"/>
			<p rend="indent(5)"><addressee>Revd. Isaac Leeser</addressee></p>
